               <p>EDWARD LANGFORD. I am ten years of age. I was in <placeName id="t18260216-131-crimeloc695">Carlisle-street, Soho</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18260216-131-crimeloc695" type="placeName" value="Carlisle-street, Soho"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18260216-131-crimeloc695" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260216-131-off692 t18260216-131-crimeloc695"></join>, on the evening of the 7th of February, about seven o'clock, with a little boy - the prisoner came up to me, and pulled my cap off; I hallooed out, and ran after him - I saw him stopped in Rose-street; I had not lost sight of him; I did not see him do any thing with it; he ran fast, and a boy said he had thrown it away - my mother is a window, and her name is Charlotte.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. I only took the cap and threw it down in the street out of a bit of fun. Witness. No; he ran a good way with it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260216-131-person872">
                  THOMAS 
                  GOOK
               <interp inst="t18260216-131-person872" type="surname" value="GOOK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260216-131-person872" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260216-131-person872" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I took the boy into custody at the witness's door - he said he had not seen the cap. I then went back, and left the young gentleman with the footman, and said the prisoner must go to the watch-house - as we were going there he said he would tell me where he had thrown it.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. I did not do it with an intent to steal.</p>
